HOL-4: Component Life Cycle

Need and benefits of component life cycle

Life cycle refers to the stages a component goes through: mounting, updating, and unmounting
It lets developers run code at specific moments, like right after a component appears
Useful for tasks like fetching data, setting up subscriptions, or cleanup
Helps avoid unnecessary work by controlling exactly when logic runs
Without life cycle methods, it would be hard to control side effects properly

Life cycle hook methods

componentDidMount(): runs once, right after the component is added to the DOM
componentDidUpdate(): runs after the component re-renders due to state/props change
componentWillUnmount(): runs just before the component is removed from the DOM
componentDidCatch(): runs when an error occurs anywhere in the component tree below it
Each hook serves a specific purpose in managing the component's behavior over time

Sequence of steps in rendering a component

Constructor runs first to initialize state
render() is called to generate the JSX/UI
The component is inserted into the actual DOM
componentDidMount() fires right after the DOM insertion is complete
Any future state/prop changes trigger render() again, followed by componentDidUpdate()

componentDidMount() hook

Called exactly once, immediately after the component first renders to the DOM
The ideal place to make API calls or fetch external data
Ensures the DOM already exists before manipulating it or triggering network requests
In this hands-on, it was used to call loadPosts() to fetch blog posts
Does not run again on subsequent updates, only on the initial mount

componentDidCatch() hook

Acts like a safety net for errors happening inside child components
Takes two parameters: the error itself and info about where it occurred
Prevents the entire app from crashing when a small part fails
Used here to show an alert message when an error occurs while loading posts
Only class components can implement this method; it has no Hook equivalent
